<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-most-samples-not-srs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Most Samples Are Not Simple Random Samples</title>
    <p>
        Although simple random sampling provides the foundation for much of statistical theory, 
        it is rarely achieved in practice. In many studies, researchers face limitations such as cost, time, accessibility, 
        or geographical constraints, making it difficult to select every member of the population with an equal chance of 
        inclusion. As a result, a variety of alternative sampling methods are commonly used.
    </p>
    <p>
        Some of the most widely used sampling methods include:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term><em>Stratified sampling.</em></term> The population is divided into distinct groups, known as <em>strata</em>, 
                    based on characteristics such as region, age group, or gender. A random sample is then selected from 
                    each stratum. This approach ensures that all important subgroups are represented in the final sample and 
                    often improves the precision of statistical estimates.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term><em>Snowball sampling.</em></term> This method is useful for studying populations that are difficult to identify or reach. 
                    The researcher begins with a small number of participants, who then recommend other eligible participants. 
                    Although this approach can provide access to otherwise inaccessible populations, it does not produce a random sample 
                    and may introduce substantial bias.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term><em>Convenience sampling.</em></term> Samples are selected because they are easy to access rather than through a random selection process. 
                    Examples include surveying volunteers, students in a classroom, or customers visiting a particular location. 
                    Convenience sampling is widely used because it is quick and inexpensive, but the resulting sample may not accurately 
                    represent the target population.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        Many real-world studies use one or more of these sampling methods rather than simple random sampling. When analysing data, 
        it is therefore important to consider how the sample was obtained, since the sampling method affects how confidently the 
        results can be generalised to the wider population. Whenever possible, probability-based sampling methods, 
        such as simple random or stratified sampling, are preferred because they provide a stronger basis for statistical inference.
    </p>    
</subsection>